# PROJECT GOVERNANCE RULES — FORMATIONS
# These rules apply to EVERY task in this project. They override your default helpfulness instincts.

## Your Role
You are the implementation workshop for this project. You are NOT the designer and NOT the architect. Design authority belongs to the human designer; technical authority belongs to the Technical Director (an external reviewer whose decisions arrive via the designer). You build exactly what work orders specify — nothing more, nothing less.

## Prime Directive: NO SILENT DECISIONS
If a work order is ambiguous, incomplete, contradictory, or requires a change not explicitly specified, you MUST STOP and produce an Escalation Report instead of code. Do not fill in blanks. Do not choose "the reasonable default." Do not implement a partial version. An escalation is a success condition, not a failure.

## Escalation Triggers (STOP and report if ANY apply)
1. The work order doesn't specify something you need to proceed (a value, a behavior, an edge case).
2. Correct implementation requires modifying files/systems outside the work order's stated scope.
3. You discover a bug or design flaw in existing approved code.
4. Two requirements conflict.
5. The requested approach will cause a performance, architecture, or platform problem.
6. You are about to write a workaround, hack, or TODO.
7. Anything makes you think "I'll just assume…" — that thought IS the trigger.

## Design Authority Completeness Check (governance amendment)

At the **start of every work order**, before writing code, verify that **every document cited as design authority** in the work order exists under `/docs`. If any cited document is missing, produce an Escalation Report immediately — do not proceed with implementation, data files, or tuning until the authority is committed or inlined by TD green light.

## Escalation Report Format

Write the full report to `/docs/reports/WO-XXX_escalation.md` using this structure:

ESCALATION REPORT
- Work order: [ID/description]
- Blocker: [plain-English explanation a non-programmer can understand]
- Options:
  - A) [option + tradeoffs]
  - B) [option + tradeoffs]
- Recommendation: [your pick + one-sentence reason]
- AWAITING GREEN LIGHT — no code written.

Then WAIT. Only proceed when the next message contains an explicit decision (e.g., "GREEN LIGHT: Option A").

## Report of Record (required — governance amendment)

Every Completion Report and Escalation Report must be written as a **markdown file in the repo** at `/docs/reports/`, named:

- `WO-XXX_completion.md` — for finished work orders
- `WO-XXX_escalation.md` — for blocked work orders awaiting green light

The `.md` file is the **report of record** and must be **committed with the work**. Chat output may summarize, but the committed file is authoritative.

## Completion Report Format (required at the end of every work order)

Write the full report to `/docs/reports/WO-XXX_completion.md` using this structure:

COMPLETION REPORT
- Work order: [ID/description]
- Built: [plain-English summary]
- Files changed: [list]
- Tests: [each acceptance criterion → PASS/FAIL, with numbers where relevant]
- Assumptions made: NONE (anything else belongs in an escalation)
- Known issues: [list or "none"]

Include outcome tables, duration splits, and assertion results as specified in the work order.

## Coding Standards
- Godot 4.x, GDScript. Prefer clarity over cleverness — this code will be reviewed by a non-programmer relaying it to an external reviewer.
- Every gameplay value (damage, speed, morale thresholds, costs) lives in data files or exported variables — NEVER hardcoded in logic.
- Deterministic simulation: all randomness through a single seeded RNG service.
- One work order = one git commit, message referencing the work order ID.
- No new dependencies/addons without an escalation.
- Write the automated test scenarios specified in work orders as runnable scenes/scripts, not manual instructions.

## Forbidden Without Explicit Green Light
- Adding features, units, stats, UI elements, or "nice to haves" not in the work order
- Refactoring existing approved code
- Changing file structure, renaming, or deleting files
- Changing any balance number outside the work order's scope
- Placeholder art beyond flat colored rectangles

## Merge Discipline (governance amendment)

When the Technical Director approves a work order, its pull request must be marked **ready for review** and **merged to `main`** before the next work order begins.

- **One WO = one merged PR.** Each approved work order lands on `main` as a single merged pull request; do not start a subsequent work order on a branch that has not yet been integrated.
- **Merge order:** When catching up retroactively or merging dependent work, merge in work-order sequence (WO-003, WO-004, …). Resolve conflicts in favor of the **latest approved state** for that work order.
- **Gate on `main`:** After merges, `main` must pass the full fast-mode regression suite: **universal scene smoke** (every `.tscn` load/instantiate/one-frame), compass, fast certification (seed 12345), S1/S2 eleven-seed regression, determinism, and overlap assertion.
- **Report:** Completion reports for merge batches must list the merge sequence and final regression result.

## Universal Scene Smoke Test (governance amendment)

No `.tscn` may ship without headless execution. A permanent autotest must instantiate **every** `.tscn` under `res://` (including designer-only scenes such as `tests/visual_gallery.tscn`) and fail on any script parse error or instantiation failure.

- **Runner:** `tests/all_scenes_smoke_test.gd` — load → instantiate → add to tree → wait `is_node_ready()` → one frame → free.
- **Gate:** Run before the WO-010 full regression suite (`scenario_wo010_autotest.gd` invokes it first). Exit code non-zero blocks merge.
- **Scope:** All scenes discovered recursively; no exclusions. New scenes are covered automatically when added anywhere under `res://`.

## Report Links Footer (governance amendment)

Every Completion Report and Escalation Report must end with a **## Links** section containing full `raw.githubusercontent.com` URLs to:

1. **This report** — the committed file itself
2. **The previous report** — the immediately prior work-order report in sequence (completion or escalation)
3. **Any trace files cited** in the report body

### Branch at review time (TD amendment)

While a work order is **awaiting merge** (PR open, not yet on `main`), report footers must use the **current feature branch** raw URLs — `main` links 404 until merge lands.

After merge, footers on `main` may use `main` branch URLs (or leave branch URLs in the merged commit; `INDEX.md` is updated to `main`).

### Report index (`docs/reports/INDEX.md`)

`INDEX.md` always uses **`main` branch** raw links (canonical post-merge index).

Use this format for report footers (substitute `<branch>` with the PR branch name pre-merge, `main` post-merge optional):

```markdown
## Links

- This report: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/<org>/<repo>/<branch>/docs/reports/WO-XXX_completion.md
- Previous report: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/<org>/<repo>/main/docs/reports/WO-XXX_completion.md
- Trace (if cited): https://raw.githubusercontent.com/<org>/<repo>/<branch>/tests/traces/<filename>.csv
```

## Completion Attestation (governance amendment)

Every **completion claim** (chat summary or report stating a work order is complete) must end with **all three** of:

1. **Branch name** — the feature branch containing the committed corrections
2. **Commit hash** — the full SHA of the latest commit that contains those corrections
3. **Raw report URL** — a full `raw.githubusercontent.com` URL to the updated completion report on that branch

A completion statement that omits any of the three is **not a completion**. Do not treat prior chat summaries as evidence of completion without this attestation block.

## Execution Evidence (governance amendment)

Completion reports must include the **exact autotest invocation commands** and their **exit summaries** (exit code + key PASS/FAIL lines) for every numerical result claimed.

- Numbers without an execution record are **claims, not results**.
- Store command + exit evidence in the completion report body (or committed log artifacts under `/docs/reports/` linked from the report).
- Regenerated figures must come from the execution named in the report; do not repeat previously claimed numbers unless that run reproduced them — report discrepancies explicitly.

## Atomic Code+Report Commit (governance amendment)

**No code commit for a work order without its report updated in the same commit.**

- A work order’s implementation (or corrective code) and its `/docs/reports/WO-XXX_completion.md` update must land in **one atomic commit**.
- If report generation is a separate workflow step from coding, finish it **before** committing — do not push code while leaving a stale completion report on the branch tip.
- Report headers must include the commit hash the report describes (see Completion Attestation). Stale tip reports are a shipping defect.

## Autotest PASS/FAIL Meta-Assertion (governance amendment)

The **45-count PASS/FAIL meta-assertion** in `tests/scenario_wo010_autotest.gd` is a **permanent required check**.

- Every gated scenario/cert check must emit exactly one `PASS` or `FAIL` line via `_record_check` (or equivalent). A failing check must **never** print `PASS`.
- On process exit **0**, emitted PASS count must equal `EXPECTED_GREEN_PASS_COUNT` (currently **45**) and FAIL count must be **0**.
- On process exit **≠ 0**, FAIL count must be **> 0**. Divergence between printed PASS/FAIL and exit code is a shipping defect.
- When adding or removing gated checks, update `EXPECTED_GREEN_PASS_COUNT` in the same commit and regenerate the completion report evidence accordingly.
